### PHP OOP - Traits

Traits allow you to reuse code across unrelated classes, solving PHP's single-inheritance limitation.

### Defining a Trait

```php
<?php
trait Timestampable {
    public $createdAt;
    public $updatedAt;

    public function setTimestamps() {
        $this->createdAt = date("Y-m-d H:i:s");
        $this->updatedAt = date("Y-m-d H:i:s");
    }

    public function touch() {
        $this->updatedAt = date("Y-m-d H:i:s");
    }
}
?>
```

### Using a Trait

```php
<?php
class Post {
    use Timestampable;

    public $title;
    public $content;
}

class Comment {
    use Timestampable, Loggable; // Multiple traits

    public $text;
}

$post = new Post();
$post->setTimestamps();
echo $post->createdAt;
?>
```

### Trait Precedence

| Priority | Source |
|----------|--------|
| 1 (highest) | Current class method |
| 2 | Trait method |
| 3 (lowest) | Parent class method |

### Conflict Resolution

```php
<?php
trait A {
    public function sayHello() {
        return "Hello from A";
    }
}

trait B {
    public function sayHello() {
        return "Hello from B";
    }
}

class MyClass {
    use A, B {
        B::sayHello insteadof A;   // Use B's version
        A::sayHello as sayHelloA;  // Alias A's version
    }
}
?>
```

### Trait vs Interface vs Abstract

| Feature | Trait | Interface | Abstract Class |
|---------|-------|-----------|----------------|
| Implementation | Yes | No | Both |
| Multiple use | Yes | Yes (implement) | No (extend) |
| Properties | Yes | No | Yes |
| Instantiate | No | No | No |

> **Key Point:** Traits are about horizontal code reuse. They solve the diamond problem and provide a way to share methods across unrelated classes.
